04563nam a22006015i 9780226429779DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20082007ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226429779  a(DE-B1597)523854  a(OCoLC)1058089836  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aRC451.A42 7aPSY0000002bisacsh04a616.89/00961a616.8900961a616.8900961090341 aKeller, Richard C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aColonial Madness :bPsychiatry in French North Africa /cRichard C. Keller. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2008] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b10 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Madness and Colonization -- t1. Pinel in the Maghreb: Liberation and Confi nement in a Landscape of Sickness -- t2. Shaping Colonial Psychiatry: Geographies of Innovation and Economies of Care -- t3. Spaces of Experimentation, Sites of Contestation: Doctors, Patients, and Treatments -- t4. Between Clinical and Useful Knowledge: Race, Ethnicity, and the Conquest of the “Primitive” -- t5. Violence, Resistance, and the Poetics of Suffering: Colonial Madness between Frantz Fanon and Kateb Yacine -- t6. Underdevelopment, Migration, and Dislocation: Postcolonial Histories of Colonial Psychiatry -- tConclusion. Pills and Paving Stones, Centers and Margins -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNineteenth-century French writers and travelers imagined Muslim colonies in North Africa to be realms of savage violence, lurid sexuality, and primitive madness. Colonial Madness traces the genealogy and development of this idea from the beginnings of colonial expansion to the present, revealing the ways in which psychiatry has been at once a weapon in the arsenal of colonial racism, an innovative branch of medical science, and a mechanism for negotiating the meaning of difference for republican citizenship. Drawing from extensive archival research and fieldwork in France and North Africa, Richard Keller offers much more than a history of colonial psychology. Colonial Madness explores the notion of what French thinkers saw as an inherent mental, intellectual, and behavioral rift marked by the Mediterranean, as well as the idea of the colonies as an experimental space freed from the limitations of metropolitan society and reason. These ideas have modern relevance, Keller argues, reflected in French thought about race and debates over immigration and France’s postcolonial legacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aColonialism. 0aMedicine. 0aPsychiatryxHistoryxAfrica, North. 0aPsychiatryzAfrica, NorthxHistory. 0aPsychiatry. 0aPsychoanalysis and colonialismxHistoryxAfrica, North. 0aPsychoanalysis and colonialismzAfrica, NorthxHistory. 0aPsychoanalysis and colonialism. 0aPsychoanalysis. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh  acolonialism, colonies, psychiatrist, psychiatry, mental health, wellness, france, french, europe, european, african, regional, academic, scholarly, research, 19th, century, writer, writing, author, travel, traveler, wanderlust, muslim, violence, sexuality, taboo, primitive, bias, geneaology, expansion, psychology, psychological, postcolonial.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022642972440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226429779423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226429779/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles